Long Island was once known as the "Potato Capital of the World," with thousands of acres dedicated to potato farming in the early to mid-20th century. The island’s sandy soil and temperate climate made it ideal for growing potatoes, and at its peak, there were over 70,000 acres of potato fields stretching across Suffolk County. Family-owned farms dominated the landscape, and the potato industry played a significant role in the local economy. While the potato fields have mostly given way to suburban development, the legacy of Long Island’s agricultural roots remains a cherished part of its history.

【Shandong Province Announces 1,100 Demand Projects for Rural Revitalization Partners】

Recently, the Human Resources and Social Security Department of Shandong Province announced 1,100 demand projects for rural revitalization partners for 2025. The projects cover all 16 cities and 136 counties (county-level cities and districts) in the province.
The submitted projects primarily focused on integrated development across primary, secondary, and tertiary related to agricultural production (48.7%), followed by crop production projects (16.5%) and new agricultural/rural business formats (7.9%).

This year, Shandong continues to welcome domestic and international talents committed to rural revitalization. The province will actively connect with the demand project units and foster comprehensive, multi-form cooperation to advance rural revitalization through flexible collaboration models and in-depth exchanges. The Human Resources and Social Security Department of Shandong Province will provide incentives to outstanding rural revitalization partners who have made significant contributions.
